Since you have a dev background, what I would recommend you trying it 

1. Take a common vulnerability type and find examples of source code where that bug was introduced
Like real examples. Not whatever toy examples you find on these learning sites
2. And study the mistake in code

3. Think about why the developer made that mistake. And how else would that kind of mistake look like in code
4. Then use github’s regex search to try and find other instances of similar (not necessarily identical) mistakes. 
> Nahamsec has a regex video out that gives some context on that

    When i ran dropbox’s bug bounty program, one of my favorite things to do was study the mistakes our engineers made to see what they mightve done wrong. 

- Perhaps it was a function they thought did one thing, but did something slightly different. 
[Wormhole Hack](https://composable-security.com/blog/6-security-sins-of-web3-bridges/)
- Maybe it was a case where they forgot to check an exception/error a function returns that had security properties. 
- Maybe there was a dangerous property in a framework they thought they used safely, but failed to consider all edge cases
- When you do source code review, you can start from the mistakes and work backwards to find ways to interact with them.

> It’s a lot easier to find the treasure in the maze, if you start at the treasure chest and work your way backwards to an entrance 🙂
> I found my auth CVE on Hashicorp’s Vault product using this exact method ^ though i was looking for a different type of mistake at the time 😄

