## ON RECON
I think the key to building automation is this

You need to have a specific methodology in mind already that is successful
Build that methodology into a tool
Run the tool

## The tool just automates your methodology. 
**You should start simple (like very simple) and go from there.** 
**I would recommend not starting with recon automation, but start with bug finding automation** 
**Recon automation is such an easy trap to get caught up in because you can always get more data**
**but ultimately we're not here to collect data**
**we're here to collect bounties. To do that, we need to find bugs.** 

Here's what I'd do

1. Screen record yourself looking for an XSS or an idor for like 5 minutes, from scratch (_start from being completely logged out so you record yourself logging in and playing with ids and such in burp/caido/etc)

2. Go back and write down the steps you took in a text file (step 1: log in, step 2: navigate to each page in the navigation bar and record all the http traffic, step 3: for each url that looks like it has an id field, try to change it to a different ID and look for a successful result, etc)

3. Now you have a text file that tells you specific steps to repeat, go and implement this. These days AI is pretty good at building simple scripts, so you can ask it to generate a tool that does these steps. Also some people are using AI to do some of this automation automatically by prompting it. You can probably lay out your methodology in a prompt and see good results that way too.
So having practice doing manual bug hunting is good because you'll at least know the steps to find a bug, but now you just need to specifically lay out what you do when you're bug hunting
if you're just haphazardly clicking around and guessing on stuff then it'll be hard to explain what you're doing, and therefore hard to automate


## NahamSec's Advice 
[How are people finding hundreds/thousands of bugs so quickly?](https://www.reddit.com/r/bugbounty/comments/dq67ea/how_are_people_finding_hundredsthousands_of_bugs/)
Depends on the hacker. If you are looking at their profile on HackerOne and their 
'impact' is ~20 or more then they are finding more than "best practices" because that means 
their bounties are more than average. For hackers that are finding 100 of bugs every year, 
it comes down to a few things:

1. Having your methodology down: Know how you look for bugs. 
How you test for them quickly to see if it's even vulnerable to specific bug classes.

2. Automation: If you are doing it more than 2-3 a day, 
you should definitely automate it so you spend your time on things that matter. 
(those 30-40 seconds add up if you do it 100 times a day + 7 times a week.

3. Recognize patterns: If you see a site vulnerable to IDOR, stick to it. 
Find as many as you can. Chances are if 2/6 random endpoints you've hit are vulnerable, 
then you can probably find more if you know how to test for them 
(knowing how to automate for this would be pretty handy)

4. Stick to a program with a big scope: The more you get to know a company the better you get at hacking them. 
This means you know what mistakes they make, how they name things, and what matters to them the most.

And of course.. practice: the more you do it the better you get at all of the points I have mentioned.

Hope this helps ;)

